{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:43:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14308"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14308"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.05,0.15,0.1,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115059"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14308"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97067"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2867"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48651"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115059"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of left lower quadrant abdominal pain. She describes the pain as constant and dull, worsening with movement. She denies fever, nausea, vomiting, or changes in bowel habits. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals localised tenderness in the left lower quadrant without guarding or rebound tenderness. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed, showing an oval fat-density lesion adjacent to the descending colon with surrounding inflammatory changes (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopic appendicectomy","Colonoscopy","Intravenous antibiotics","Percutaneous drainage","Oral NSAIDs and outpatient follow-up"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation and CT findings are consistent with appendagitis, also known as epiploic appendagitis. This is a benign, self-limiting condition caused by torsion or thrombosis of an epiploic appendage, which are small pouches of fat attached to the colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral NSAIDs and outpatient follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for appendagitis. The condition is self-limiting and typically resolves within 3-14 days with conservative management. NSAIDs help manage pain and reduce inflammation. Patients should be advised to return if symptoms worsen or fail to improve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic appendicectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for appendagitis. This surgical procedure is used for acute appendicitis, which presents differently and has distinct CT findings. Appendagitis does not require surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not necessary for appendagitis as it is not an infectious process. Antibiotics are typically reserved for conditions like diverticulitis or appendicitis where bacterial infection is present or suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for appendagitis. This procedure is used for draining abscesses or fluid collections, which are not features of appendagitis. The CT scan in this case shows only inflammatory changes without any drainable collection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the acute management of appendagitis. While it may be considered in cases where there is concern for underlying colonic pathology, it is not necessary for diagnosing or treating appendagitis itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to differentiate appendagitis from other causes of right lower quadrant pain, such as acute appendicitis or diverticulitis. CT scan is the preferred imaging modality for making this distinction. The key to managing appendagitis is recognizing its benign, self-limiting nature and avoiding unnecessary invasive interventions or antibiotic use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Appendagitis is a self-limiting condition that typically resolves with conservative management.","CT scan is the preferred imaging modality for diagnosing appendagitis.","NSAIDs are the mainstay of treatment for appendagitis pain."],"references":["Giannis D, Matenoglou E, Sidiropoulou MS, et al. Epiploic appendagitis: pathogenesis, clinical findings and imaging clues of a misdiagnosed mimicker. Ann Transl Med. 2019 Dec;7(24):814. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6989878/","Ekladious A, Bhandari R. Epiploic appendagitis: a commonly undiagnosed non-surgical acute abdominal emergency. Intern Med J. 2023 Jul;53(7):1265-1268. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37474462/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97067"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14308"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22132"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22132","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22132"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9Xgujk6vedCGc28h8mQqtMFtzdHnSY.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9Xgujk6vedCGc28h8mQqtMFtzdHnSY.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":716,"height":716}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97067"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T08:27:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T08:29:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7003"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115059"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,